      </div>
      <div class="block-content">
        <p>Clear revision policies help ensure projects stay on track and within budget. Understanding the difference between included revisions and scope changes is essential for a smooth project experience. This section defines what constitutes a revision versus a new request and how each is handled.</p>

        <p><strong>Included Revisions:</strong></p>
        <ul class="policy-list">
          <li><strong>Website Projects:</strong> Standard packages include 2 rounds of revisions. Each round allows you to request changes to any aspect of the current deliverable.</li>
          <li><strong>Chatbot Projects:</strong> Includes 2 rounds of training data adjustments and 1 round of appearance/behavior modifications.</li>
          <li><strong>Design Work:</strong> Initial design concepts are followed by 2 revision rounds based on your feedback.</li>
          <li><strong>Revision Definition:</strong> A revision is a modification to existing work that stays within the originally agreed scope. Examples include color changes, text updates, layout adjustments, or feature tweaks.</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>What Is NOT a Revision (Scope Changes):</strong></p>
        <ul class="policy-list">
          <li><strong>New Features:</strong> Adding features, pages, or functionality not specified in the original agreement.</li>
          <li><strong>Design Direction Change:</strong> Significantly changing the design direction, style, or aesthetic after work has begun.</li>
          <li><strong>Content Expansion:</strong> Adding substantially more content than originally specified.</li>
          <li><strong>Platform Changes:</strong> Switching to a different platform, hosting provider, or technical approach mid-project.</li>
          <li><strong>Requirement Changes:</strong> Modifying fundamental project requirements or business objectives.</li>
          <li><strong>Re-do Requests:</strong> Asking to revert to previous versions or restart work that was already approved.</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Additional Revision Charges:</strong></p>
